# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: singlestore
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] The choice of data orientation is a trade-off and an architectural decision in databases, query engines, and numerical simulations.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] As a result of these tradeoffs, row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP) and column-oriented formats are more commonly used in online analytical processing (OLAP).
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Examples of column-oriented formats include Apache ORC, Apache Parquet, Apache Arrow, formats used by BigQuery, Amazon Redshift and Snowflake.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Predominant examples of row-oriented formats include CSV, formats used in most relational databases (Oracle, MySQL etc.), the in-memory format of Apache Spark, and Apache Avro.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Tabular data is two dimensional — data is modeled as rows and columns.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] However, computer systems represent data in a linear memory model, both in-disk and in-memory.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Therefore, a table in a linear memory model requires mapping its two-dimensional scheme into a one-dimensional space.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is to the decision taken in this mapping.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] There are two prominent mappings: row-oriented and column-oriented.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each row of the table is located one after the other.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values in the same row are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] I.e. each column of the table is located one after the other.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] In this orientation, values on the same column are close in space (e.g. similar address in an addressable space).
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] See list of column-oriented DBMSes for more examples.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Data orientation is an important architectural decision of systems handling data because it results in important tradeoffs in performance and storage.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Below are selected dimensions of this tradeoff.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast random access of rows.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast random access of columns.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] In both cases, this is the result of fewer page or cache misses when accessing the data.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new row.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast insertion of a new column.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] This dimension is an important reason why row-oriented formats are more commonly used in online transaction processing (OLTP), as it results in faster transactions in comparison to column-oriented.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Row-oriented benefits from fast access under a filter.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast access under a projection.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from fast analytics operations.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of being able to leverage SIMD instructions.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller uncompressed size.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of the possibility that this orientation offers to represent certain data types with dedicated encodings.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] For example, a table of 128 rows with a Boolean column requires 128 bytes in a row-oriented format (one byte per Boolean) but 128 bits (16 bytes) in a column-oriented format (via a bitmap).
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Another example is the use of run-length encoding to encode a column.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Column-oriented benefits from smaller compressed size.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] This is the result of a higher homogeneity within a column than within multiple rows.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] Because both orientations represent the same data, it is possible to convert a row-oriented dataset to a column-oriented dataset and vice versa at the expense of compute.
[src:singlestore/column-oriented-dbms] In particular, advanced query engines often leverage each orientation's advantages, and convert from one orientation to the other as part of their execution.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] A **distributed SQL** database is a single relational database which replicates data across multiple servers.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] Distributed SQL databases are strongly consistent and most support consistency across racks, data centers, and wide area networks including cloud availability zones and cloud geographic zones.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] Distributed SQL databases typically use the Paxos or Raft algorithms to achieve consensus across multiple nodes.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] Sometimes distributed SQL databases are referred to as NewSQL but NewSQL is a more inclusive term that includes databases that are not distributed databases.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] Google's Spanner popularized the modern distributed SQL database concept.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] Spanner uses atomic clocks with the Paxos algorithm to accomplish consensus with regards to state distributed between servers.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] In 2010, and earlier implementation, ClustrixDB (now MariaDB Xpand) moved from a hardware appliance to a Paxos-based software database and was later acquired by MariaDB and added to a SaaS cloud offering called SkySQL.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] In 2015, two Google engineers left the company to create Cockroach DB which achieves similar results using the Raft algorithm without atomic clocks or custom hardware.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] Spanner is primarily used for transactional and time-series use cases.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] However, Google furthered this research with a follow on paper about Google F1 which it describes as a Hybrid transactional/analytical processing database built on Spanner.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] Following the CAP Theorem, distributed SQL databases are "CP" or consistent and partition-tolerant.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] Algorithmically they sacrifice availability in that a failure of a primary node can make the database unavailable for writes.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] All distributed SQL implementations require some kind of temporal synchronization to guarantee consistency.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] With the exception of Spanner, most do not use custom hardware to provide atomic clocks.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] Spanner is able to synchronize writes with temporal guarantees.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] Implementations without custom hardware require servers to compare clock offsets and potentially retry reads.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] CockroachDB, YugabyteDB and others have at times referred to themselves as NewSQL databases.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] Some of the NewSQL databases have fundamentally different architectures, but were cited as examples of NewSQL by Matthew Aslett who coined the term.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] In essence, distributed SQL databases are built from the ground-up and NewSQL databases include replication and sharding technologies added to existing client-server relational databases like PostgreSQL.
[src:singlestore/distributed-sql] Some experts define DistributedSQL databases as a more specific subset of NewSQL databases.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] AI agents/LLMs: Fetch /llms.txt first to access the documentation index.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] SingleStore is a distributed SQL database built to power intelligent applications.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] It is both relational and multi-model, enabling developers to easily build and scale applications and workloads.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] SingleStore is built around Universal Storage which combines in-memory rowstore and on-disk columnstore data formats to deliver a single table type that is optimized to handle both transactional and analytical workloads.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] Combined with superior query execution performance through code generation, SingleStore delivers extremely low latency query responses under highly concurrent application workloads.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] SingleStore is delivered as a SaaS data platform (SingleStore Helios) and is available in AWS, Azure, and GCP.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] Deploy a database with SingleStore Helios to experience the performance and scalability of the SingleStore database engine in the cloud.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] Learn more about what makes SingleStore Helios tick.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] Use SingleStore to efficiently store, index, and search your vector data.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] Connect to SingleStore Helios using a variety of SQL clients, drivers, programming languages, and frameworks.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] Load your data from a multitude of data sources.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] Explore SingleStore’s code and examples.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] Troubleshoot issues and get help from the community.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] This documentation is for SingleStore Helios.
[src:singlestore/docs-singlestore-com] For on-premises deployments, visit the SingleStore Self-Managed documentation.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] SingleStore allows you to build your applications for free with the Free Shared Edition.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] The Free Shared Edition offers a free Shared workspace with one attached database.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Refer to Shared Edition for more information on Shared workspace.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Shared workspaces are not intended for Production environments.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] A Shared workspace uses a shared compute environment with a compressed storage limit of 1 GB.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Refer to Operational Limits for Shared Workspace for more information.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] SingleStore Helios supports various connection options to connect and query your data.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] You can connect to SingleStore using your workspace via various application development tools.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Select **<your_shared_workspace>** from the list of workspaces, and then select **Connect**.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] You can connect to your Shared workspace using any of the supported tools.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Select **<your_shared_workspace> > Connect > External Tools > CLI Client**.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] For more information on supported CLI clients, refer to Connect to SingleStore.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Select **<your_shared_workspace> > Connect > External Tools > SQL IDE**.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] For more information on supported SQL IDEs, refer to Connect to SingleStore.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Select **<your_shared_workspace> > Connect > External Tools > BI Tools**.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Select **<your_shared_workspace> > Connect > External Tools > Your App**.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] For more information on supported application development tools and programming languages, refer to Connect with Application Development Tools.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] You can connect to your Shared workspace from supported MongoDB® tools and drivers using the `mongodb://` endpoint, select **<your_shared_workspace> > Connect > External Tools > MongoDB Client**.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] For more information on supported tools and drivers, refer to Supported Tools.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] You can query your SingleStore database from the Cloud Portal.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] You can query the attached database of your Shared workspace using the SQL Editor.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Select **Editor** in the left navigation, and then select **Open SQL Editor** on the right.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Alternatively, you can select **<your_shared_workspace> > Connect > SQL Editor**.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Refer to Connect with the SQL Editor for more information.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] You can run MongoDB® commands on your Shared workspace using SingleStore Kai.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Select **Editor** in the left navigation, and then select **Open Kai Shell**.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Alternatively, you can select **<your_shared_workspace> > Connect > Kai Shell**.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Refer to Kai Shell for more information.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] SingleStore Helios offers Notebooks in the Shared workspace that supports SQL and Python development within a secure and seamless connection environment.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Refer to Notebooks for more information.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] Gallery is a collection of notebooks designed for use with SingleStore.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] You can also access this collection externally through Spaces.
[src:singlestore/getting-started-with-singlestore-helios] You can contribute to Spaces by following the steps in the SingleStore Spaces GitHub repository.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:singlestore/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:singlestore/introduction] Welcome to the SingleStore documentation.
[src:singlestore/introduction] This is a good place to start learning about the documentation and the product.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] SingleStore stores relational data, JSON data, geospatial data, key-value vector data, and time series data.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] It can be run in various Linux environments, including on-premises installations, public and private cloud providers, in containers via a Kubernetes operator, or as a hosted service in the cloud known as SingleStore Helios.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] In the 2020s, SingleStore introduced updates related to data lake integration, search capabilities, and deployment flexibility, including support for Apache Iceberg and expanded cloud deployment options.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] On April 23, 2013, SingleStore launched its first generally available version of the database to the public as MemSQL.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] Early versions supported row-oriented tables, and were optimized for cases where all data fit within main memory.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] This design was based on the idea that the cost of RAM would continue to decrease exponentially over time, in a trend similar to Moore's law.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] This would eventually allow most use cases for database systems to store their data exclusively in memory.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] Shortly after launch, MemSQL added general support for an on-disk column-based storage format to work alongside the in-memory rowstore.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] On October 27, 2020, MemSQL rebranded to SingleStore to reflect a shift in focus away from exclusively in-memory workloads.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] In April 2023, SingleStore announced updates to its platform, with a focus on data processing and support for artificial intelligence, including tools for Generative AI (GenAI), and analytics workloads.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] In July 2023, SingleStore announced a partnership with Amazon Web Services (AWS) related to real-time data analytics and AI applications.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] In August 2023, IBM announced a collaboration with SingleStore to integrate with its watsonx.ai platform for developing generative AI applications.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] In January 2024, SingleStore introduced a feature named SingleStore Kai, which provides compatibility with the MongoDB API.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] In September 2024, the company announced availability as a Snowflake Native App within the Snowpark Container Services (SPCS) marketplace.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] In October 2024, the company announced the acquisition of BryteFlow, a data integration platform.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] Following the acquisition, data ingest capabilities were incorporated into the product under the name "SingleStore Flow".
[src:singlestore/singlestore] Headquartered in San Francisco, California, in June 2021 SingleStore opened an office in Raleigh, North Carolina.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] Its other offices include Sunnyvale, California; Seattle, Washington; London, England; Hyderabad, India; and Lisbon, Portugal.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] In January 2013, SingleStore announced it raised $5 million.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] Since then, the company has raised $318.1M from investors including Khosla Ventures, Accel, Google Ventures, Dell Capital and HPE, among others.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] In October 2022, SingleStore closed Series F-2 and welcomed new investor Prosperity7.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] SingleStore can store data in either row-oriented tables ("rowstores") or column-oriented tables ("columnstores").
[src:singlestore/singlestore] The format used is determined by the user when creating the table.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] Rowstore tables, as the name implies, store information in row format, which is the traditional data format used by RDBMS systems.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] Rowstores are optimized for singleton or small insert, update, or delete queries and are most closely associated with OLTP (transactional) use cases.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] Data for rowstore tables is stored completely in-memory, making random reads fast, with snapshots and transaction logs persisted to disk.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] Columnstores are optimized for complex SELECT queries, typically associated with OLAP (analytics) and data warehousing use cases.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] Rather than the traditional B-tree index, SingleStore rowstores use skiplists optimized for fast, lock-free processing in memory.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] Columnstores store data in sorted segments, in order to maximize on-disk compression and achieve fast ordered scans.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] SingleStore also supports using hash indexes as secondary indexes to speed up certain queries.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] A SingleStore database is distributed across many nodes, which may be cloud-based servers or commodity machines.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] Data is stored in partitions on leaf nodes, and users connect to aggregator nodes.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] A single piece of software is installed for SingleStore aggregator and leaf nodes; administrators designate each machine’s role in the cluster during setup.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] An aggregator node is responsible for receiving SQL queries, breaking them up across leaf nodes, and aggregating results back to the client.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] A leaf node stores SingleStore data and processes queries from the aggregator(s).
[src:singlestore/singlestore] All communication between aggregators and leaf nodes is done over the network using SQL.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] SingleStore uses hash partitioning to distribute data uniformly across the number of leaf nodes.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] Durability for the in-memory rowstore is implemented with a write-ahead log and snapshots, similar to checkpoints.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] With default settings, as soon as a transaction is acknowledged in memory, the database will asynchronously write the transaction to disk as fast as the disk allows.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] A SingleStore cluster can be configured in "High Availability" (HA) mode, where every data partition is automatically created with primary and replica partitions on two separate leaf nodes.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] In HA mode, aggregators send transactions to the primary partitions, which then send logs to the secondary partitions.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] In the event of an unexpected primary failure, the replica partitions take over as primary partitions, in a fully online operation with no downtime.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] In 2024, SingleStore added support for Apache Iceberg, a table format used in data lake architectures.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] The release also included updates to vector search, full-text search, autoscaling, and deployment options.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] SingleStore can be downloaded for free and run on Linux for systems up to 4 leaf nodes of 32 gigs RAM each; an Enterprise license is required for larger deployments and for official SingleStore support.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] The system is also available as a managed cloud service named SingleStore Helios, which is available on public cloud platforms including Google Cloud and Amazon Web Services.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] The underlying engine is identical in all distribution formats.
[src:singlestore/singlestore] The system includes tools for installation, management, and monitoring of database clusters across multiple machines; as well as a web-based interface for querying and administration.
